    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">
&amp;gt;From GROSS:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="23" relname="span">

&amp;gt; Well, maybe.  But how about responding substantively to the
&amp;gt; substantive arguments made by such fascist beasts as Gross and
&amp;gt; Levitt.  Is it not remotely possible that they--and other &quot;elite&quot;
&amp;gt; scientists--would respond? </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="31" relname="span">

Of course they will respond--</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="22" relname="span">and it&apos;s as easy as one-two-three
what they will say.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration">  (See HAMLETT&apos;s posting.) </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="preparation"> I believe that
I made myself clear:</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="27" relname="span"> rationality in and of itself leads nowhere
when one is in a position of inferiority. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="concession"> Reasonable and 
strong as our arguments may be,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="25" relname="span"> they will go nowhere with
people who are biased such as yourself. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="condition"> But not only that,
even if you were convinced, </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="26" relname="span">they would go nowhere,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="24" relname="span"> because
their implications have serious ramifications on the status
quo. </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="12" relname="elaboration"> (For one thing, the budding niche from which some of these 
Big scientists are making a nice living would be disrupted.  </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="29" relname="span">
Ineed, it&apos;s an interesting twist (with many hints to the larger cultural,
political, etc., context) to the old story of glorifying science 
to have creepy  and weird creatures crawling around now. </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="28" relname="span"> It adds drama 
and suspense </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="15" relname="background">(Weinberg and Wolpert devote a chapter each to us), </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="14" relname="elaboration">
a nice detour and a fresh thing to confront, to the usual run-of-the-mill, 
and after a while, boring and predictable Science Story). </segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="34" relname="span">

&amp;gt; Your strategy, rather, is to Get the
&amp;gt; Bastards from behind, isolate them from the &quot;malcontents&quot; of
&amp;gt; science (your word), and go on to Victory.  Sounds familiar.
&amp;gt; Quite a few of the tyrants of history have set that strategy down
&amp;gt; in writing.</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="32" relname="span">

Yes, with your conception of what history is about (remember, folks,
it&apos;s _muddleheadedness_ that is at the root of all humankind&apos;s ills)</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="19" relname="elaboration">
I need not worry too much. </segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="19" relname="elaboration"> All the same, watch your back....</segment>
